# Server Configuration
# STOA_PORT is the port knob — honoured by the `stoa` CLI, `stoa doctor`, AND
# `npm run dev` (it is bridged to PORT on startup; if both are set, STOA_PORT wins).
STOA_PORT=3011

# ── Auth (token) + remote sharing ──
# A single shared token gates access (Jupyter-style); loopback is TRUSTED by default,
# so local use is frictionless. The token is auto-generated to ~/.stoa/token, or set
# STOA_TOKEN=<token> to pin one. STOA_AUTH=off disables auth entirely (never do this
# on an exposed host).
# STOA_TOKEN=
#
# STOA_REQUIRE_AUTH=1 makes even LOCALHOST require the token. This is REQUIRED before
# `stoa share`: a tunnel (Tailscale funnel / cloudflared) reaches the server FROM
# localhost, so without it a public share would grant access with no token. Keep it
# set for as long as you share; `stoa share` refuses to start otherwise.
# STOA_REQUIRE_AUTH=1

# Database — path is relative to the directory Stoa is started from.
DB_PATH=./stoa.db

# ── Running two Stoa instances on the same machine ──
# (e.g. a dev server from your checkout + a separately-installed copy)
#
# The one that silently bites: both default to the same Tier-2 terminal-daemon
# pipe, so they'd share one daemon — a stop/restart on one kills the other's
# live terminals. Give each a UNIQUE name (uncomment + change on one of them):
# STOA_PTY_HOST_NAME=stoa-dev
#
# The other two are softer: pick a distinct STOA_PORT per instance (a taken port
# fails to start — it does NOT auto-increment), and DB_PATH is already separate
# when instances run from different folders, so only override it if they share one.

# ── Rate-limit auto-resume (opt-in) ──
# When an agent hits a provider rate/usage limit, Stoa detects it and (only if
# this is set to 1) resumes the session once the reset time has passed — turning
# dead overnight hours into throughput. Detection + the "limited / resets in N"
# badge are always on; the unattended resume is what this gates. Off by default.
# STOA_AUTO_RESUME=1
#
# Hardening (so the resume is SAFE, not a footgun — applies only when auto-resume
# is on). Two safety knobs default-ON; the capability knob defaults OFF:
#  • A per-session DAILY CAP so a flapping limit can't be nudged endlessly
#    overnight (default 8; high enough that real use never hits it; 0 = unlimited).
#    Stoa also never nudges a session that's actively working — only one idly
#    parked at the limit ("still parked where you left it").
# STOA_AUTO_RESUME_MAX_PER_DAY=8
#  • A FALLBACK window (ms): when the limit notice carries NO parseable reset time,
#    resume this long after it was first seen instead of waiting forever. OPT-IN —
#    default 0 (off: a no-reset limit waits for the agent/user). 300000 = 5 min.
# STOA_AUTO_RESUME_FALLBACK_MS=300000

# ── Auto-answer routine prompts (opt-in) ──
# When an agent stalls on a routine prompt, Stoa (only if this is 1) presses Enter
# so an overnight fleet run doesn't wait on a 2am question. SAFETY is structural:
# Enter only ever takes the HIGHLIGHTED single-shot "Yes" of a permission menu (or
# an explicit "Press Enter to…" / "[Y/n]" default) — it can't flip a No to Yes or
# grant a blanket "allow all / don't ask again". A best-effort denylist (rm -rf,
# force-push, terraform destroy, del/rd, …) is extra defense-in-depth; anything
# blanket, destructive-looking, or unrecognized is left for you (still pushed as
# "needs your input"). Detection is always on; the unattended Enter is what this
# gates. Off by default.
# STOA_AUTO_ANSWER=1

# ── One-tap push Approve (opt-in) ──
# Adds an "Approve" button to the lock-screen push for a waiting session, so you can answer
# from your phone. The tap presses Enter, RE-VERIFIED server-side at tap time. Offered ONLY for
# a structurally-benign "Press Enter to continue" / "[Y/n]" prompt — a permission MENU's Yes and
# any blanket/destructive/free-text prompt stay attention-only (you swap to the app), since a
# lock-screen tap can't show the gated command. Separate from STOA_AUTO_ANSWER (that auto-presses
# unattended; this needs your tap). Off by default → notifications stay attention-only.
# STOA_PUSH_APPROVE=1

# ── Auto-/compact (opt-in) ──
# Proactively reclaims a Claude session's context window BEFORE it fills, so a long /
# overnight run doesn't stall in (or crash from) the painful auto-compaction. With this
# set to 1, when a Claude session's context occupancy reaches the threshold below AND the
# session is at a clean IDLE boundary (agent at rest, no prompt up — never mid-turn, never
# hijacking a question), Stoa sends `/compact`. A cooldown prevents re-compacting before
# the transcript-derived reading catches up, and a per-session daily cap backstops a
# runaway loop if context stays high. SAFETY mirrors the other unattended writers: it fires
# only at the canonical idle-AND-no-prompt boundary (never into an open permission/input
# dialog). Like every paster, it inserts at the cursor — so a half-typed user draft would
# get `/compact` appended; the threshold+cooldown+cap gating keeps that rare. Claude-only
# (`/compact` is a Claude command). Off by default; like auto-resume it WRITES, hence opt-in.
# STOA_AUTO_COMPACT=1
# STOA_AUTO_COMPACT_AT=0.85          # compact at this fullness (fraction or percent; clamped 0.5..0.99; default 0.85)
# STOA_AUTO_COMPACT_COOLDOWN_MS=300000   # min gap between compactions (default 5m; floored at 60s)
# STOA_AUTO_COMPACT_MAX_PER_DAY=12   # per-session daily cap; 0 = unlimited (default 12)

# ── Error-loop escalation (opt-in) ──
# When a session gets STUCK — its turn ends on the same error and that error sits
# there for ~90s (a narrow provider-failure envelope, not normal output) — Stoa
# (only if this is 1) sends ONE "stuck in a loop" push so you step in, instead of
# finding it dead in the morning. ESCALATE-ONLY: the terminal is never written to,
# so a false positive costs one extra notification, never a derailed agent. A
# changing error or a flip back to working resets it. Off by default.
# STOA_ERROR_LOOP=1
# STOA_ERROR_LOOP_THRESHOLD=4       # consecutive same-error ticks (2.5s each), AND…
# STOA_ERROR_LOOP_WINDOW_MS=90000   # …the same error must persist this long

# ── Self-healing watchdog (opt-in) ──
# Keeps an unattended fleet from dying silently. Two independent, default-off knobs.
#
# 1) Hung Dispatch worker. A worker that never opens a PR or exits pins its
# concurrency slot forever. Set a wall-clock ceiling (ms) past which a still-live
# worker is reaped → 'failed', freeing the slot (the pty is left alone so you can
# still inspect it). 0/unset = never reap by age (today's behavior). Set this
# ABOVE your longest expected worker runtime so a slow-but-healthy worker survives.
# STOA_DISPATCH_WORKER_MAX_AGE_MS=7200000   # e.g. 2h
#
# 2) Wedged session. A session whose spinner never settles (a hung request, a
# frozen TUI) reads as "running" forever and you never find out. With this set to
# 1, Stoa sends ONE "may be stuck" push once a session has run continuously past
# the ceiling below. ESCALATE-ONLY: the terminal is never written to, so a false
# positive costs one extra notification, never a derailed agent. Any turn boundary
# resets the streak, so a normally-iterating agent never pages. Off by default.
# STOA_AUTO_WATCHDOG=1
# STOA_WATCHDOG_STUCK_MS=1800000    # continuous "running" before paging (default 30m)
#
# The two knobs are independent and can overlap: a wedged Dispatch worker may BOTH
# get a "may be stuck" push (knob 2) and later be reaped to free its slot (knob 1).
# That's intended — one tells you, the other reclaims the slot.

# ── Proactive rate-limit backoff (opt-in) ──
# PROACTIVE complement to auto-resume (which is REACTIVE — it nudges a session that
# already hit the wall). When Claude's binding rolling rate-limit window (the 5h/7d
# quota, surfaced by the M2b statusline hook in ~/.stoa/rate-limits.json) is at/above
# this threshold, the Dispatch reconciler HOLDS new Claude workers — it won't start
# work that would immediately stall. Candidates stay pending (FIFO) for a later,
# less-saturated tick; sessions already at the limit are still drained by auto-resume.
# Claude-only (the window is Claude-account-specific); a no-op if the M2b hook isn't
# installed (no data → never throttles). It also spares a throttled worker from the
# age-reaper above (knob 1) while saturated. Accepts a FRACTION (0.9) or a PERCENT
# (90); unset/0/garbage = OFF (today's behavior). Off by default.
# STOA_DISPATCH_RATELIMIT_BACKOFF=0.9

# ── Inter-agent channel delivery (opt-in) ──
# Channels are a 1:1 message bus between sessions: agents send/read direct messages
# via the channel_* MCP tools (and /api/channels). That PULL path is always on —
# an agent reads its inbox on demand. This flag adds the optional PUSH: at a
# recipient's next clean turn boundary (settled + no open prompt), Stoa injects ONE
# unread message into its terminal with a directive "this is from another agent,
# reply with channel_send" wrapper, one message in flight at a time. Off by default
# because writing into a session unattended is the risky part (same stance as
# STOA_AUTO_RESUME). With it off, a recipient simply polls channel_inbox.
# STOA_AUTO_CHANNEL_DELIVER=1

# ── Dispatch issue intake — Linear (opt-in) ──
# Dispatch pulls issues from an issue tracker behind ONE interface. GitHub (via
# the `gh` CLI) is the DEFAULT and needs no config here. To point a tracked repo
# at Linear instead, give its slug a `linear:` prefix where the remainder is the
# Linear TEAM KEY (e.g. `linear:ENG`); Dispatch then queries Linear's GraphQL API
# over HTTPS. That path needs a Linear personal API key in LINEAR_API_KEY (create
# one under Linear → Settings → API). Unset ⇒ the Linear path degrades to "no
# issues this tick" (logged), exactly like an unauthenticated `gh`. GitHub repos
# are unaffected. (Jira intake is not implemented yet — a `jira:` slug falls back
# to GitHub with a warning.)
# LINEAR_API_KEY=

# ── Background cost sampling (opt-in) ──
# Stoa persists a daily token/cost sample per session into the session_costs table
# so the spend history (the sparkline in the cost badge) survives a session being
# deleted or its transcript scrolling off. History already accrues whenever the cost
# panel is open (that request persists a sample). This flag adds an unattended tick
# (~5 min) so it keeps accruing on an overnight run with nobody watching. Read-only
# w.r.t. sessions (it only computes cost and writes the table — never touches a
# terminal), so it's safe to leave on; it's opt-in only to keep default DB writes
# unchanged. Off by default.
# STOA_AUTO_COST_SAMPLE=1

# ── OpenTelemetry GenAI trace export (opt-in) ──
# Export GenAI-semantic-convention spans (per run + MCP tool call) to any
# OTLP/HTTP collector — instant Langfuse / Grafana / any-OTEL compatibility.
# A hard NO-OP unless STOA_OTEL_ENDPOINT is set: nothing is built, no network is
# touched, and no clock is read when it's unset. Emit is best-effort and bounded
# (5s per-request timeout, capped in-flight) so a slow/down collector can never
# stall or fail a run. STOA_OTEL_ENDPOINT is the base OTLP/HTTP endpoint (the
# standard /v1/traces path is appended) or a full traces URL; it must be http(s)
# or export stays off. STOA_OTEL_HEADERS adds auth/extra headers as comma-
# separated key=value pairs. Off by default.
# STOA_OTEL_ENDPOINT=http://localhost:4318
# STOA_OTEL_HEADERS=Authorization=Bearer your-token,x-tenant=acme
